00:54.788 --> 01:07.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Reports are just
beginning
to trickle in tonight, but
already it's clear

01:07.534 --> 01:12.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hurricane Matthew has sent
long-suffering
Haiti even deeper into misery.

01:12.739 --> 01:16.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's word of at least seven
dead and widespread
wreckage.

01:16.376 --> 01:18.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: This is Matthew.

01:18.512 --> 01:20.380 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Pray for us!

01:20.414 --> 01:26.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's one of the
fiercest Caribbean
storms in years, and its
powerful core roared

01:26.920 --> 01:35.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over the southwestern tip of
Haiti before
dawn, with winds of 145 miles an
hour.

01:35.095 --> 01:41.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Emergency officials reported
major damage,
roots ripped apart, trees torn
out of the

01:41.568 --> 01:46.573 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ground, and roads and bridges
underwater.

01:46.606 --> 01:51.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Forecasters had said the storm
would dump
as much as 40 inches of rain on
the poorest

01:51.745 --> 01:53.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
country in the Americas.

01:53.780 --> 01:57.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jacqueline Charles is a reporter
from The
Miami Herald.

01:57.451 --> 02:00.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She spoke from Port-au-Prince,
the Haitian
capital.

02:00.420 --> 02:05.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACQUELINE CHARLES, The Miami
Herald: We have
rivers that are beginning to
rise.

02:05.959 --> 02:09.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's one major bridge that
connects the
capital with the north.

02:09.196 --> 02:14.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And police basically blocked
traffic from
using that bridge because it's
now become

02:14.034 --> 02:16.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a dangerous situation.

02:16.103 --> 02:21.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: After crossing
Haiti, the hurricane's
center moved on during the day
to strike Eastern

02:21.541 --> 02:27.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cuba tonight, not far from the
U.S. Naval
base at Guantanamo Bay.

02:27.881 --> 02:32.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Its approach sent people fleeing
across the
region.

02:32.719 --> 02:35.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN (through translator): Last
night was terrible.

02:35.689 --> 02:40.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The waves were enormous, to the
point where
I thought they were going to
enter the house.

02:40.093 --> 02:41.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They were very big.

02:41.461 --> 02:43.230 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They were worse than now.

02:43.263 --> 02:47.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Overnight, the
slow-moving
Matthew is set to barrel through
the Eastern

02:47.367 --> 02:49.202 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bahamas.

02:49.236 --> 02:54.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's projected to head toward
Florida at the
end of the week, and push its
way up the U.S.

02:54.341 --> 02:56.143 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
East Coast over the weekend.

02:56.176 --> 03:01.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, Florida Governor Rick
Scott was out
telling people to start getting
ready without

03:01.748 --> 03:02.716 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
delay.

03:02.749 --> 03:04.651 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

03:04.685 --> 03:06.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK SCOTT (R), Florida: Once
this storm comes,
we cannot put our
first-responders in harm's

03:06.153 --> 03:07.120 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
way.

03:07.154 --> 03:09.456 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You must leave before it's too
late.

03:09.489 --> 03:13.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can rebuild a home, you can
rebuild a
business, you cannot rebuild a
life.

03:13.226 --> 03:18.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Hurricane watches
are now up
for the southeastern parts of
Florida.

03:18.198 --> 03:23.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And farther up the coast, South
Carolina's
governor has announced plans to
evacuate one

03:23.870 --> 03:25.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
million people.

03:25.806 --> 03:29.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for the very latest on
Matthew, we turn
to the National Hurricane
Center.

03:29.409 --> 03:34.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I spoke with its director, Rick
Knabb, in
Miami just a short time ago.

03:34.347 --> 03:36.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Rick Knabb, welcome.

03:36.049 --> 03:39.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First of all, where is this
storm right now?

03:39.586 --> 03:43.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK KNABB, Director, National
Hurricane Center:
Right now, Hurricane Matthew is
centered in

03:43.890 --> 03:48.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between Haiti and Eastern Cuba,
will clip
the eastern tip of Cuba this
evening.

03:49.029 --> 03:51.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then it will be headed toward
the Bahamas.

03:51.231 --> 03:55.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's still going to be
impacting Haiti
and Cuba for many, many hours to
come.

03:55.068 --> 03:56.369 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's not just a point on a map.

03:56.403 --> 04:00.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a pretty big and powerful
hurricane,
still a Category 4.

04:00.273 --> 04:05.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not just about wind either,
heavy rainfall,
likely flash floods and
mudslides affecting

04:05.145 --> 04:09.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Haiti and the Dominican
Republic, and that
could spread into Eastern Cuba,
and then the

04:10.016 --> 04:12.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bahamas, hurricanes warning for
the entire
length of the Bahamas.

04:12.319 --> 04:14.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're going to be impacted
starting tomorrow.

04:14.421 --> 04:18.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You said it's a
powerful storm.

04:18.325 --> 04:21.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Compared to other hurricanes,
how do you describe
it?

04:21.695 --> 04:28.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK KNABB: It is similar to
many other past
major hurricanes that are
Category 3 or stronger

04:28.435 --> 04:31.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on our five-tier hurricane wind
scale.

04:31.938 --> 04:35.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Matthew's sustain winds are
140 miles
per hour.

04:35.375 --> 04:40.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So those are the maximum winds,
but the tropical
storm-force winds can extend out
to almost

04:40.113 --> 04:41.815 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
200 miles from the center.

04:41.848 --> 04:44.284 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So it's a big and powerful
system.

04:44.317 --> 04:48.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we're really concerned
about is a
large number of folks in the
Bahamas being

04:48.388 --> 04:51.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
impacted, but also then we're
forecasting
this turn to the northwest.

04:51.791 --> 04:57.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Florida, and Georgia, South
Carolina, North
Carolina are all threatened,
with Florida

04:57.430 --> 05:02.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being first, hurricane watches
in effect for
portions of the southeast coast
of Florida.

05:02.302 --> 05:06.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We even had to extend that a
little farther
south to include Broward County,
the Fort

05:06.072 --> 05:08.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lauderdale area, here at 5:00
p.m.

05:08.441 --> 05:15.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what are you
able to determine
in terms of how strong it's
going to stay?

05:15.549 --> 05:21.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK KNABB: It's not going to
interact with
land enough to significantly
weaken it.

05:21.488 --> 05:25.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's good that it's not spending
too much
time over Eastern Cuba tonight.

05:25.959 --> 05:28.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, as it's over the
Bahamas, that's
mostly a water environment.

05:28.762 --> 05:31.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The islands there probably are
not going to
cause it to weaken.

05:31.665 --> 05:36.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The waters are very warm, the
atmosphere conditions
still conducive for this to
remain a major

05:36.536 --> 05:39.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hurricane for the next few days.

05:39.639 --> 05:46.079 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that means it's not
impossible for a major
hurricane to make landfall
somewhere in the

05:46.112 --> 05:48.014 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
state of Florida this week.

05:48.048 --> 05:52.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's also possible for
hurricanes to directly
or indirectly impact Georgia,
South Carolina,

05:52.886 --> 05:54.754 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and North Carolina.

05:54.788 --> 05:58.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we have been talking to
emergency managers
in all of these areas today, and
we urge folks

05:58.892 --> 06:01.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to pay attention, do whatever
their local
officials are telling them to
do.

06:02.028 --> 06:07.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here in South Florida, where
we live,
today and tomorrow and tomorrow
night is the

06:07.500 --> 06:12.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time left to prepare before the
weather starts
going downhill down here on
Thursday morning.

06:12.272 --> 06:16.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Rick Knabb,
when is the
next alert you're going to be
issuing?

06:16.643 --> 06:22.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK KNABB: We issue full
updates, with a
complete new forecast every six
hours.

06:22.849 --> 06:26.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that will happen again at
11:00 p.m. Eastern
time tonight.

06:26.386 --> 06:30.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We do issue intermediate public
advisories
every three hours in between to
update on

06:30.957 --> 06:36.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the intensity and on the
position as we continue
to fly hurricane hunter aircraft
into and

06:36.162 --> 06:37.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
around the hurricane.

06:38.031 --> 06:42.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the next complete forecast
and major changes
that we would potentially
communicate with

06:42.202 --> 06:46.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
watches and warnings will happen
again at
11:00 p.m. and then again at
5:00 a.m.

06:46.039 --> 06:49.509 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, people on the East Coast of
the U.S.,
just don't tune out.

06:49.542 --> 06:52.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And take preliminary
preparations, so you
know what you're going to do if
watches and

06:52.679 --> 06:54.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
warnings are issued for your
area later.

06:54.614 --> 06:57.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I know
everyone is going
to be paying very close
attention.

06:57.984 --> 07:00.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rick Knabb with the National
Hurricane Center,
we thank you.

07:00.987 --> 07:03.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICK KNABB: Thank you, Judy.

07:03.590 --> 07:08.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: In the day's other
news: The way
is now clear for the Paris
climate change

07:08.561 --> 07:09.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
accord to take effect.

07:10.030 --> 07:13.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
